  "response": "Several countries without traditional armies use different strategies for defense:\n\n1. Costa Rica\n- No standing army since 1948\n- Relies on police forces\n- Has mutual defense agreements with neighboring countries\n- Depends on international law and diplomacy\n\n2. Iceland\n- NATO member with collective defense agreement\n- No standing army, but has a Coast Guard\n- Relies on other NATO countries for military protection\n\n3. Vatican City\n- Swiss Guards provide security and ceremonial protection\n- Relies on Italy for external defense\n\n4. Liechtenstein\n- No military\n- Relies on Switzerland for defense\n- Maintains neutrality\n- Emphasizes diplomatic solutions\n\n5. Monaco\n- No military\n- Relies on France for defense through treaty\n- Has local police force for internal security\n\n6. Alternative defense strategies\n- Diplomatic negotiations\n- International treaties\n- Collective defense agreements\n- Strong economic and political alliances\n- Investing in conflict prevention\n- Maintaining neutrality\n- Developing robust intelligence and cybersecurity capabilities\n\nThese countries typically prioritize peaceful conflict resolution, maintain good international relations, and rely on international organizations like the UN for protection.",
